  "prompt": "What are some less fictioned movie everyone must watch?",
  "response": "Okay, let's delve into some compelling, less-fictioned movies that offer valuable perspectives and insights, often based on real events or exploring significant social issues. I'm focusing on documentaries, biographical dramas, and films rooted in reality, but with a strong focus on storytelling that resonates.\n\n**Documentaries (Thought-Provoking & Insightful):**\n\n*   **\"Icarus\" (2017):**  Initially about doping in sports, it unexpectedly uncovers a massive Russian state-sponsored doping program. A gripping real-time thriller with global implications.\n*   **\"Free Solo\" (2018):**  An absolutely breathtaking and nerve-wracking account of Alex Honnold's ropeless climb of El Capitan.  It's about ambition, risk, and the human spirit.\n*   **\"The Act of Killing\" (2012) & \"The Look of Silence\" (2014):** These companion pieces confront the perpetrators and survivors of the Indonesian mass killings of 1965-66. Utterly chilling and profoundly important in understanding the lingering effects of genocide.\n*   **\"13th\" (2016):** Ava DuVernay's powerful exploration of the history of racial inequality in the United States, focusing on the prison-industrial complex.\n*   **\"Man with a Movie Camera\" (1929):** A silent documentary masterpiece. A beautiful collage of a day in the life of Soviet cities and an exploration of the very nature of filmmaking. It's incredibly experimental and influential.\n*   **\"Amy\" (2015):**  A tragic and intimate portrait of Amy Winehouse, using archival footage and interviews to show her rise and struggles.\n*   **\"Honeyland\" (2019):**  A visually stunning and deeply moving documentary about a Macedonian beekeeper who uses traditional methods, and the challenges she faces when modern beekeeping disrupts the delicate balance of nature.\n*    **\"Flee\"(2021):** A deeply personal and creative story of a refugee's journey that blends animation and documentary elements.\n*   **\"Collective\" (2019):** A Romanian documentary that follows an investigative team of journalists uncovering corruption in the healthcare system after a tragic fire. It's a gripping look at the power of investigative journalism and the fight for accountability.\n\n**Biographical Dramas & Films Based on True Events:**\n\n*   **\"Spotlight\" (2015):** The true story of the Boston Globe's investigative team that uncovered the Catholic Church's child sex abuse scandal.  A powerful testament to journalistic integrity.\n*   **\"Schindler's List\" (1993):** A heartbreaking but essential film about Oskar Schindler, who saved the lives of over a thousand Polish-Jewish refugees during the Holocaust.\n*   **\"The Imitation Game\" (2014):**  The story of Alan Turing and his team's efforts to break the Enigma code during World War II.  A celebration of intellect and a reminder of the human cost of prejudice.\n*   **\"The Social Network\" (2010):** A fictionalized, but compelling, account of the creation of Facebook.  It raises questions about ambition, friendship, and the impact of technology.\n*   **\"Hidden Figures\" (2016):**  The inspiring true story of three African-American women mathematicians who played a vital role in NASA's early space missions.\n*   **\"Apollo 13\" (1995):**  A gripping and accurate portrayal of the real-life Apollo 13 mission, highlighting the ingenuity and teamwork required to overcome a near-disaster in space.\n*   **\"Catch Me If You Can\" (2002):** Based on the true story of Frank Abagnale Jr., a con artist who posed as various professionals. A fascinating look at deception and the FBI pursuit.\n*   **\"Erin Brockovich\" (2000):**  A single mother becomes a legal assistant and uncovers a cover-up involving contaminated water in a small town. A great story of an average person fighting for justice.\n*   **\"Argo\" (2012):**  A CIA exfiltration specialist concocts a risky plan to rescue American diplomats from Tehran during the Iran hostage crisis. A tense and thrilling true story.\n*   **\"The Wolf of Wall Street\" (2013):** A biographical dark comedy about the excesses of Jordan Belfort and the culture of greed on Wall Street. It's a cautionary tale about unchecked ambition.\n*   **\"First Man\" (2018):** A more introspective look at Neil Armstrong and the sacrifices made in the quest to land on the moon. It's not just about the mission, but the personal toll.\n*   **\"Judas and the Black Messiah\" (2021):** A powerful and gripping story about the betrayal of Fred Hampton, chairman of the Black Panther Party, by an FBI informant.\n\n**Films Addressing Social Issues (Based on Reality):**\n\n*   **\"Parasite\" (2019):** Although fictional, it is a razor-sharp depiction of class disparities in South Korea (and resonant globally).\n*   **\"Nomadland\" (2020):**  While fictional, it's a deeply realistic portrayal of a woman who travels the American West as a modern-day nomad after losing everything in the Great Recession.  It offers a poignant look at resilience and community.\n*   **\"Roma\" (2018):**  A semi-autobiographical film by Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n that depicts a year in the life of a middle-class family in Mexico City in the early 1970s.  It's a beautiful and intimate portrayal of domestic life and the experiences of indigenous women.\n*   **\"Doubt\" (2008):**  Set in a Catholic school in 1964, it explores themes of faith, power, and suspicion when a nun suspects a priest of inappropriate behavior.  While fictional, it tackles important issues of abuse of power and the challenges of seeking truth.\n*   **\"I, Daniel Blake\" (2016):**  A British film about a widowed carpenter who struggles to navigate the bureaucratic system to receive welfare benefits.  It's a powerful and moving portrayal of poverty and social injustice.\n*   **\"The Florida Project\" (2017):** A poignant and heartbreaking look at childhood poverty in the shadow of Disney World. While the characters are fictional, the circumstances are very real for many families.\n\n**Important Considerations when Choosing:**\n\n*   **Your Interests:** What topics or areas are you most curious about?\n*   **Emotional Tolerance:** Some of these films can be emotionally challenging.\n*   **Availability:** Check streaming services, libraries, or rental options.\n\nThis is just a starting point, of course!  There are countless other fantastic less-fictioned films out there.  Enjoy your viewing!\n",
